				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sun Apr 13, 2008 11:12 am<br /><b>Posts:</b> 7391<br /><b>Location:</b> Seattle
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The stupid trick:<br /><div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
			<a href="./download/file.php?id=7342&amp;mode=view"><img src="./download/file.php?id=7342&amp;t=1" alt="i2cslavemapper.png" /></a><br />
			<span class="gensmall">i2cslavemapper.png [ 20.52 KiB | Viewed 3077 times ]</span>
		

		<br />
	</div><br /><div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
			<span class="genmed">
				<img src="./styles/subsilver2/imageset/icon_topic_attach.gif" width="14" height="18" alt="" title="" /> 
				<a href="./download/file.php?id=7341">i2cslavemapper.gp5.zip</a> [3.6 KiB]
			</span><br />
			<span class="gensmall">Downloaded 57 times</span>
		

		<br />
	</div><br /><br />I lied, actually.<br /><br />We can get a full MMC3/VRC4 experience out of a GreenPAK.<br /><br />Remember how I said that, like FPGAs, the GreenPAKs run out of RAM? Sure, they have a one-time-programmable ROM, but it's used to preload the RAM.<br /><br />As long as it's configured to be permissible, each of the LUTs can have their tables set using I²C. So all you need is something that can talk I²C to it to change banking.<br /><br />Since we lost two of our pins to the I²C interface, we're even more heavily I/O limited now. That's why I've implemented only 2×16 PRG banking (256 KiB max) and 8×1 CHR banking (32 KiB max—I'm assuming CHR-RAM). And the LUTs are <em>transposed</em> from how the NES would find useful. (i.e. you can't just say &quot;this byte specifies what CHR bank is present from $0000-$03FF&quot;; instead you have to say &quot;here's the value for CHR A10 for each of the eight CHR banks&quot;). And the LUTs are partially but not entirely contiguous: e.g. 3LUT0-3LUT4 are five sequential bytes, but 3LUT5-3LUT10 are a separate block of six bytes.<br /><br /><br />It gets crazier. The I²C master can change the <em>entire</em> configuration of the GreenPAK (as long as it's allowed to). Connectivity, LUT contents, counter limits. Want a mapper that will automatically change banks at scanline N? Want to use the 7 counters as a polyphonic sound IC?<br /><br />The only thing you can't do after the fact is change how it's soldered.<br /><br /><br />Next time: a fast I²C interface, hopefully. (I'm not done yet)</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
